    "summary": "The Yalta Conference, held February 4–11, 1945, in the Crimean resort city of Yalta, brought together the leaders of the three major Allied powers — Franklin D. Roosevelt of the United States, Winston Churchill of the United Kingdom, and Joseph Stalin of the Soviet Union — to discuss the reorganization of Europe and the postwar world as Germany faced imminent defeat. The conference produced agreements on the division of Germany into occupation zones, the framework for what would become the United Nations, the conditions for Soviet entry into the war against Japan, and the political future of Poland and Eastern Europe.\n\nThe agreements on Eastern Europe proved most consequential and most controversial. Stalin agreed to free elections in Poland and other liberated states, but the Soviet interpretation of free elections differed fundamentally from Western understanding. Soviet forces already occupied most of Eastern Europe, and Stalin's promises proved difficult to enforce. Poland's eastern border was moved westward, compensating Poland with German territory while incorporating parts of prewar Poland into the Soviet Union.\n\nYalta became intensely controversial in subsequent decades, with critics accusing Roosevelt of naively conceding Eastern Europe to Soviet domination. Defenders argued that Roosevelt had little leverage given Soviet military dominance on the ground and that the agreements represented a reasonable diplomatic outcome under the circumstances. The conference established the broad framework within which the [[event:113|Cold War]] division of Europe would develop.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yalta_Conference",
